This application is part of a broader approach I use to streamline engineering workflows by combining engineering logic with modern technology.

What you’re seeing here is a tablet-based site inspection application, designed to eliminate manual steps between field work and final documentation.

We start by entering an address — for demonstration purposes, we can use any location.
From there, parameters such as directions and order types are selected.
All of these elements are fully configurable, allowing the workflow to adapt to different project requirements.

In the next step, we select an order type.
Based on that selection, the system dynamically generates a structured inspection form.

This form supports multiple input types — including checkboxes, text fields, and configurable options — making it easy to capture exactly what the inspection requires without unnecessary complexity.

The goal at this stage is accuracy and consistency, ensuring the right data is collected in the field in a structured way.

The next step in the workflow is photo documentation.

The system includes five predefined photo categories, which helps maintain consistency across inspections — for example, front, right-side, and left-side views of the site.

For demonstration purposes, I’m uploading sample images from my computer.
In a real field scenario, these photos would be captured directly on site using a tablet or mobile device.

Once the inspection data and photos are completed, we submit the inspection.
After the final commit, the system automatically generates a structured PDF report.

This report combines all inspection data with the related photos into a single, professional document — ready for review, submission, or archiving.

The key idea behind this workflow is efficiency.
By automating reporting, this approach removes manual work, reduces errors, and significantly shortens the time between site inspection and deliverable-ready documentation.

This structure is not limited to a single use case.
It can be adapted for different engineering inspections, control processes, or field workflows.

It’s a practical example of how engineering tasks can be accelerated by designing workflows that combine engineering standards with flexible, technology-driven tools.